{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_andrews_ver01/data/sn84020645/00513684381/1910122001/1302.xml":{"full_text":"T\nSELMA DISAPPOINTED\nWITH GEOS FIGURES\nFederal Enumeration Gives Popu\nlation of 13,659\nDECREASE IN THREE YEARS\nFormer Travcllac Mas Oeta lata Tron\nkle_Wholesale Grocer? Baalaeaa\nikaaarca Haada\u2014Beard\u2018of Director.\nU IMMtot Orpkaaace Will Mad.\nSELMA, ALA., Dec. l#.\u2014Selma baa a\npopulation of* 13,668 according to the\nrecent census and which figures were\nreceived here this afternoon by Con\ngressman William B. Craig, in a tele\ngram from E. Dana Durand, director\nof the census bureau, i\nThe figures show there has been a\ndecided decrease In the number of in\nhabitants during the past three years\nand they are disappointing to a ma\njority of the residents.\nA few years ago when the Legisla\nture passed a law that the saloons In\nall cities should be closed at a certain\nhour each night the city authorities\nauthorized a census to see If Selma\nsaloons could keep open until 9\no'clock. That census was carefully\ntaken and when the figures were com\npiled It showed the city had a popula\ntion of about 17,000.\nAfter the government census was\ntaken last spring a school census of\nthe city was taken. This latter cen\nsus was also disappointing for It show\ned Selma with a population slightly\nover 14,000. But with the government\ncensus figures and the figures of the\nschool census very close there will\nbe registered no kick.\nThe panic of two years ago caused\nhundreds of residents of this city\nto leave and make their homes In oth\ner Cities. Many of the Industries of\nthe city were closed down and they\nhad to move to some other place to\nfind employment. With the return of\nprosperity and the establishment of\nnew Industries some of the old resi\ndents are moving back and new peo\nple are coming to make their homes\nhere where they are finding steady\nemployment and while the census fig.\nures are lower than was expected\nevery resident knows Selma has a\nsteady growth.\nTraveling Man In Trouble.\nE. A. Trigg, a white man, was ar\nrested by police officers late Sunday\nafternoon on the charge of bringing\nBtolen property Into the city. Trigg\nwas unable to make bond for his ap\npearance In court this morning and\nspent the night In the city prison.\nThe case against the young man was\ncalled In police court this morning\nbut was continued until Tuesday\nmorning and as Mr. Trigg has been\nunable\u2018to make bond he will spend to\nnight In prison also.\nIn connection with the arrest of Mr.\nTrigg, Mable Dean, a white woman,\nwas arrested Sunday night on a war\nSoft White\nHands\nRed, rough hands on retiring\nusually become soft, white\nhands on rising through this\nsimple and economical \u201cone\nnight\u201d treatment: Bathe and\nsoak the hands on retiring,\nin a strong, hot lather of\nCuticura Soap. Dry and\nanoint freely with Cuticura\nOintment, and wear during\nthe night old, loose gloves, or\na light bandage to protect the\nclothing. Most effective for\nchapped, itching, burning\nand bleeding hands.\nBend to Potter Dntg A Chem. Oorp., Ben\nton. tor tree boon on cnr\u00ab of tbn akin.\nI\nrant which alio charged here with\nbringing etolen property into the\ncity.\nFor more than two years Mr. Trigg\ntraveled the tSelma territory for a\nforeign house and made this city his\nheadquarters. Later ne.was employed\nin the store of Eliasberg Brothers on\nBroad street and a little over a year\nago moved from Selma to Montgom\nery. Some months ago he came -back'\nto Selma and later went to work for\nA. J. Flnlayson at Hamburg, Perry\ncounty. 4\nMr. Trigg was arrested at the re\nquest of Perry oounty authorities. It\nis alleged that Saturday while emp\nloyed at Mr. Flnlayson'a place of bus\niness in Hamburg he took between\n$600 and $800 and came to Selma that\nnight and went to a house on North\nstreet. For that reason the woman,\nMabel Dean, was arrested In connec\ntion. When arrested none of the mon\ney which it Is alleged he had taken\nwas found upon Mr. Trigg.\nBusiness Changes Hsads.\nA deal was concluded this morhlng\nby which Leon Selgle. F. M. Scott, E.\nM. Cothran and Jerome Selgle bought\nthe wholesale grocery business of\nNathan Kahn and Son at the corner of\nWater and Broad streets. The new\nfirm Ig composed of well known young\nmen of this city.\nThe particulars regarding the deal\nwere not made public today nor was\nthe style name In the future made\nknown. Mr. Kahn has made no plans\nfor the future but as he has been a\nresident of Selma for a great many\nyears he will continue to make this\ncity his home.\nWill Hold lasportaat Meeting.\nThe board of directors of the Ala\nbama Methodist Episcopal'Orphanage\nwhich is located at Summerfleld, nine\nmiles from Selma, will hold an impor\ntant meeting here tomorrow and dur\ning which arrangements will be com\npleted for the paying off of every cent\nof Indebtedness against that Institu\ntion.\nWith the present debt lifted from\nthe orphanage the board of directors\nnropose in future to run the Institu\ntion on a cash basis. In this endeavor\nthey will no doubt receive the support\nof the Methodists of the State. The\nmeeting which will be held tomorrow\nwas called some davs ago by Mr J\nB. Flowers of Dothan, who Is the\nnresldent of the board.\nr\n1 .SELMA SOCIETY\nMr\u00ab. Adler HoctdiR.\nSTCLMA, ALA., Dec. 19.\u2014Mri. J. 0.\nAdler was hostess this afternoon at\nher home on Broad Street, when she\nentertained at a beautiful and elabor\nate bridge luncheon In compliment to\nher daughter, Mrs. Ephrlam Ball of\nNorfolk, and two other charming visit\ning matrons, Mrs. Nomar Goldsmith\nof Charleston, and Mrs. Max Fles of\nIlirmlngham. About twenty guests\n\u00abere present and bridge was played\nat five small tables, arranged In the\nreception room and parlor, which were\ntastefully decorated with potted plants\nand festoons of smllax.\nThree trophies were awarded, two\nnovel wrought Iron candlesticks and a\nlovely doll pin holder.\nLater the guests were Invited Into\nthe dining room where a sumptuous five\ncourse luncheon was served at a table\nresplendent In Us appointments of ele\ngant silver, cut glass and flowers.\nCovers were laid for twenty. On one\nend of the table was arranged a mound\nof smllax having a gilt-wheeled wagon\ncornucopia-shaped and made of pink\ncrepe paper. In this wagon was seat\ned a beautiful doll, daintily dressed In\npink hand painted silk and holding\npink ribbons attached to the place\ncards, tiny dolls forming pin holders.\nFlat mirrors surrounded by smllax,\nI moss and pink, forget-me-nots, and\nsurmounted by small swans, effective\nly represented miniature lakes. From\nI the chandelier above the table was sus\ni pended an artistic arrangement of pink\ntulle and festoons of smllax. Among\nthose present were: Mesdames Ball,\nGoldsmith, Fles, Powarney of New Or\nleans, Morris Hohenberg, Albert Thal\nhelmer, Henry Lilienthal. M. J. Meyer,\nClara Kohn, C. L. Rosenberg, Morris\nRosenberg, Arthur Loeb, Hary Marlng,\nAaron Maas, J. c. Adler. August\nRothschild, Lena Wolf, Julius Sternfeld,\nAlbert Meyer, Lee Adler, Jacob Kap\nlan, Misses Cora Schneider of Buffalo\nand Jennie Hohenberg.\nSocial and Personal.\nSaturday's Birmingham News con\ntained a splendid picture of Mrs. R. E.\nL. Nlel of this city, with the fol\nlowing complimentary remarks: \"She\nIs an enthusiastic worker for the pro\nposed Morgan-Pettus memorial, and Is\neditor of the Womans\u2019 Department of\nThe Selma Times. She Is also a leader\nof society and an active philanthrop\nist.'*\nMiss Elsie Hooper, who attends\nschool at Baltimore, will arrive home\nshortly for the Christmas holidays.\nMiss Hattie Jones who attends Hol\nlins Institute In Virginia, will visit\nMiss Leila Lamar during the holidays.\nMessrs. Harrison Atkins, John Land.\nDavid Vaughan, Jr.. Clarence Grayson,\nSidney Coleman and Claude Chisholm,\nwill arrive home In a day or so from\nthe State University to spend the holi\ndays here with relatives.\nDr. Clarence Elebash Is here from\nNew York on a visit to relatives.\nMr. Frank Hurley, of Montgomery,\nspent Sunday here with frltnds.\nTemporary Heat Quickly\nDid you ever stop to think of the many ways In which a\nperfect oil heater is of value P If you want to sleep with your win\ndow open In wither, you can get sufficient heat from an oil heater\nHUIo you undress at night, and then turn it off. Apply a match\niu me morning, wnen you get out or\nbed, and you have heat while you dress.\nThose who have to eat an early\nbreakfast before the stove is radiating\nheat can get immediate warmth from\nan oil heater, and then turn it off.\nThe girl who practices on the piano\nIn a cold room in the morning can\nhave warmth from an oil heater while\naheplays, and then turn it off,\nThe member of the family who\nhas to walk the floor on a cold win\nter\u2019s night with a restless baby can get\ntemporary heat with an oil heater, and\nthen turn it off. The\nAbsolutely smokeless and odorless\nIs Invaluable In Its capacity of quickly giving heat. Apply a match and It is lm*\nmediately at work. It will burn for nine hours without refilling. It is safe,\nsmokeless and odorless. It has a damper top and a cool handle. An indicator\nalways shows the amount of oil in the font.\nIt has an automatic-locking flame spreader which prevents the\nwick from being turned high enough to smoke, and la easy to remove and drop\nback so that the wick can be cleaned in an instant.\nThe burner body or gallery cannot become wedged, and can be quickly\nunscrewed for rewicking. Finished. In japan or nickel, strong, durable, well\nmade, built for service, and yet light and ornamental.\nDealers Everywhere. If not at yours, writs for descriptive circular\nto the nearest agency of the\nStandard Oil Company\n(Incorporated)\nMOBILE REVENUE BOARD\nHUS SPIRITED SESSION\nDecided Split In Membership\nDevelops Early.,\nOFFICERS ARE ELECTED\nCharges of Mlraaiattaeit la Road\nAffairs Briars oa Lively Parley\u2014As\neoaataat Calls Attemtloa to Cfcaaco\nfor Fraad at Coaaty Jail;\nMOBILE. ALA., Dec. U\u2014One of the\nlongest and by far the most strenuous\nsessions of a Board of Revenue and\nRoad Commissioners was that held to\nday.. It was the second regular ses\nsion of the new body and early devel\noped the fact of a division with\n'Bauer, Andrews and Green, on one\nside, with Brannon and Hagan on the\nother.\nComplaint as to roads first occupied\nattention, all of which were referred\nto a committee.\nOfficial notice of the election of Dr.\nJ. T. England by the Mobile Medical\nSociety sb County Physician was re\nceived and tiled.\nNine bids for plumbing at the poor,\nasylum were opened and \"referred to\nthe Finance Committee.\nReports of the Road Superintend\nent and overseers precipitated the fun\ntbhlch flowed fast and furious for a\ntime.\nCommissioner Ho\u00abar started the fun\nby saying the Board was lnerror In\nemploying labor for the county roads.\nHe cited the fact that Overseer Hinson\nemployed twenty-eight men In a pre\ncinct whlch only had twenty-three\nvoters. He said white cooks were\nhired and insisted negroes could be\nemployed for much less.\nCommissioner Andrews took Issue\nwith Commissioner Hagan and said\nmen could not be secured for less than\n$1.60 per diem to do road work.\nCharges Against Overseer.\nCharges were made that Overseer\nHinson put his men to work at 7 a. m.\nand \u201cknocked them oft\" at 5 p. m..\nafter traveling from live to seven\nmiles, leaving the work at S o'clock.\nHinson denied the charge emphatical\nly. Commissioner Hagan charged that\nRoad Overseer Stanton left his gang\nat 10 o'clock In the morning and went\nto his home at Coden on several Sat\nurdays.\nCommissioner Andrews said that It\nwas strange the complaints did not\ncome to the Road Committee.\nCommissioner Hagan said that he Is\nInformed that the Road Committee\nsmuggled the reports.\nCommissioner Andrews said It was\nstrange all the \u201csoreheads'* in ths\ncounty wrote letters to Commissioner\nHagan.\nThe discussion Anally abated as to\nroad matters and other business was\ntaken up.\nWasson Street, In Whistler, leading\nto North Mobile, was ordered opened;\nalso the old military road at Kipling.\nExpert Accountant Lockwood made\na line report on the books of the Infe\nrior Criminal Court.\nReport of Accountant.\nLockwood called attention to the\nchance for fraud by the jailer In ac\ncepting money and allowing prisoners\nto go free without even having to\nchange the reading of the sentenoe.\nCommissioner Hagan asked the.\nCounty Attorney if it was fair for the\ncounty to have double Ins and outs on\ncases where the prisoners give bond\nand then uome back to jail on appeal\nand give another bond. Commissioner\nHagan said that If the SherifI ob\ntained any money Illegally the Com\nmissioners should go back on the\nbondsmen.\nThe report was, on motion of Com\nmissioner Hagan, referred to the Fi\nnance Committee and County Attorney\nto report back at another meeting.\nCommissioner Green offered a reso\nlution as follows, which was adopted:\n\u201cThat the various supplies for the\ncounty be let out by contract for a pe\nriod of three months to the best and\nlowest bidder.\n\u201cThat bids be Invited for groceries,\nclothing, feed and fuel to the county\npoor asylum for fuel and clothing for\nthe county Jail; for stationery and\nprinting supplies to the county offices;\nfor hay, corn, oats, lumber and all\nsupplies for road account.\nElection of Officers.\nThe Board went Into the election of\nuiuceia, commissioner* Hagran and\nBrannon asking to be excused from\nvoting. They claimed that did not\nwant to participate In the election as\nto only two officers, Road Overseer in\nthe Second District, and Keeper of Dog\nRiver Bridge.\nThe following officers were elected,\nonly Commissioners Bauer, Andrews\nand rGeen voting: County Attorney,\nG. J. Sullivan; Keeper of Poor Asy\nlum, Thomas B. Murray; Court House\nengineer, Harry O. Murray. Applica\ntions for the position of Keeper of\nthe Poor Asylum were made by Murray\nand the present superintendent, John\nSimmons. Murray received all three\nvotes. The term was made four years.\nThe term of the engineer was made\nfour years. Court House night watch\nman oJhn Brown, term of four years;\nHenry Kenney (relected for four years)\ncustodian of record room In .Probate\nOffice; W. II. Baxter (re-elected four\nyears); overseers, first district, M. T.\nKearns, John Batiste.\nWhen vote for Second District came\nup Commissioner Brannon nominated\nWiley Denmark and Hagan seconded,\nbut they were told they had ignored\nthe board by not voting on others.\nWalter Vigor was elected, also James\nSheltun; Third District, Joe Stevens and\nFrank N. Stanton. It was decided to\nhold up the appointments of road over\nseers until It was learned if Vigor,\nwho is a school commissioner, could\nserve It. II. McCarthy was elected\ntender of Dog River bridge.\nThe time for the inspection of the\ncounty roads as provided for by law\nwas fixed for February and October.\nMay Purchase Automobile.\nIt was suggested that the commis\nsioners purchase an automobile for the\npurpose of inspecting the roads but tills\nwas not allowed.\nCommissioner Hagan criticised the\nformer road committee for being a one j\nman power, and said that he hoped\nthat the entire committee under the j\npresent administration would control\naffairs and look after the road work. I\nPresident Bauer announced the ap\npointment of the following committees\nfor the next six months, the former\nterm being four years:\nFinance Committee\u2014John T. Bauer,\nchairman; Charles Green. John D.\nHagan.\nRoad Committee\u2014Charles Green, j\nchairman; F. P. Andrews, Henry Bran- j\nnon\nPoor Asylum\u2014John D. Hagan, chair- 1\nman; Charles Green. Henry Brannon.\n.lull Committee\u2014F. P. Andrews.\nchairman; Charles Green, Henry Bran\nnon\nCourt House Committee\u2014Henry\nRrannon, chairman; John D. Hagan,\nF. P. Andrews.\nLegislative Committee\u2014John D. Ha\nfan. chairman; John T. Bauer, F. P.\nAndrrews, Churles Green, Henry Bran\nnon\nEXAMINATIONS FOIl TEACHERS.\nBAY MINETTE. ALA Dec. 19.\u2014Un\nder the direction of County Superin\ntendent of Education Rev. J. S. I,am\nliert. about thirty teachers from the\nvarious schools of the county and a\nnumber who are aspiring to become\nteachers, took an examination to se\ncure licenses tilts morning. The ex\namination will last two days, the\nschools whose teachers are taking the\nexamination, being- closed until the\nlatter part of the week.\nXkw deacons installed.\nBAT MINETTE. Dec. IS.\u2014The new\ndeacons and deaconesses of the Bur\nkett Memorial Presbyterian church of\nthis plwace were Installed at the even\ning service Sunday. The new deacons\nare Dr. J. M. Smith. W. S. Fruden.\nFrank B. Nlhart and Summer R.\nStapleton, the deaconesses are Mrs,\nPattle X* Gilmer. Mrs. Jay P. Mix, Mrs.\nJ. C. McLeod and Miss Grace Aylln.\nThe service was very Impressive.\nTEACHERS AT RED BAY.\nRegular Session of the Fraaklla Conn,\nty Teachers\u2019 Institute.\nRED BAY. ALA., Dec. 19.\u2014The\nFranklin County Teachers' Institute,\nheld In the auditorium of the High\nSchool building, was conducted by\nCounty Superintendent T. H. Robin\nion. There were thirty-two teachers,\nrepresenting most every section of the\nsc-unty. Mrs. Sarah Bruckner, of\nMontgomery, Prof. W. L. Yarber,\nprincipal of the County High School;\nC. E. Rlcheson, Representative-elect\nof the county, were present.\nProf. E. T. Boling, principal of the\ntown school, and Mayor W. R. John\nson welcomed the members on behalf\nof the town. J. E. Hester -responded\nIn a Very appropriate talk. The\nteachers discussed several very Im\nportant subjects, but we would re\nfer especially to Civics and Health,\nEducational Needs In Alabama, and\nthe Local Teachers\u2019 Reading Circle.\nThe county was laid oft into districts\nand temporary presidents appointed\nto organize reading ciacles to meet\nand discuss the course outlined by the\nState Department.\nThe Institute adjourned after hav\ning spent two pleasant and profitable\ndays to meet at a time and place to\nbe called by the County Superintend\nent.\nMOBILE SOCIETY\nChristmas Dance.\nMOBILE, Dec. IS.\u2014Misa Rosamond\nRobbins, wlio has been a much feted\ndebutante was given a lovely dance\nthis evening at the home of her pa\nrents, Mr. and. Mrs. J. Sydney Rob\nbins on Hamilton street. The decor\nations were entirely the Chiratmas\ncolors. The rooms were filled witli\nSouthern smilax and from these gar\nlands were suspended innumerable red.\nThe large galleries were enclosed and\nalso decorated In the Christmas col\nors and here punch was served\nthroughout the evening.\nAt midnight a buffet supper was\nserved after which dancing was kept\nup until the \"wee small hours.\u2019*\nThe debutantes and all the young\ndancing set were out In force and each\nand every one had a Joyous time.\nMiss Robbins, a pretty felonde, look\ned particularly pretty in a handsome\ngown of white lace and she carried\nwhite roses and ferns.\n*W*r tor Brow s-McCary Bridal\nParty.\nAfter the rehearsal this evening.\nMiss Pearl McCary entertained very\nattractively for the members of her\nbridal party at the home of her pa\nrents, Mr. ar.d Mrs. George W. McCary.\n16 Espejo street.\nRoses and ferns formed the decora\ntions for the rooms and table where\na tempting supper was served.\nSeveral musical selections were\ncharmingly rendered during the even\ning and those present,, besides Miss\nMcCary and Mr. Brown, wore the brid\nal party. Miss Mamie Seymour of\nOcean Springs, Mr. and lira G. A.\nIlelmer, Mr. Joe Brown and a number\nof friends.\nDinner at the Cnwfhon.\nA quartote who enjoyed a dinner\nat the Cawthon Vineyard last evening\nwas composed of Miss Rosa Coates,\nDr. Quest of Louisville, Ky., and Mr.\nand Mrs. Junius Woolf.\nHamilton Whist CInb.\nMrs. Millard Kirkhrlde was hostess\nfor the Hamilton Whist Club this af*\nternoon at 3 o\u2019clock, the prizes were\nsilver picture frumeH and those who\nPlayed were Mesdatnes J. T. Cochrane,\nH. P. Vass, G. M. Luce. Henry Hall,\nMinor Friend, Joseph Hodgson, W. A.\nPowell, J. W. Woolf, Harry Donald,\nand Miss Mabel Heustts.\nAnnouncements.\nThe M. M. I. Christmas Hop will\ntake place at German Relief Hall on\nWednesday evening at 8 p. m.\nOn Tuesday evening at 8 p. m. the\nt7. M. 8. hop will take place at Ger\nman Relief Hall. t\nOn Wednesday evening, Mrs. W. C.\nFitts will entertain at cards In com\npliment to Misses Sadie Shields, Mary\nHagan and Harriet Fitts.\nOn Thursday afternoon at 3 o'clock,\nMrs. Harold Reed will give a card par\nty in compliment to Miss Katherine\nDonald.\nPersonal Note*.\nMiss Ruth McQowln arrived home\nyesterday from \u201cCastle on Hudson\" to\nspend the holidays with her parents,\nMr. and Mrs. J. F. McQowln.\nAmoni? the visitors for the holiday\nseason that Mobile gladly welcomes Is\nMrs. Charles T. Hearin and her at\ntractive young' daughter, Miss Jamie\nHearin. Mrs. and Miss Hearin are\nthe guests of Captain and Mrs. John\nQuill.\nMr. Kenneth Donald will arrive from\nYale on Friday for \u00a3he holidays.\nMr. and Mrs. William F. Stephenson\nof Toledo, O., are expected soon to vis\nit Mrs. Stephenson\u2019s sister, Mrs. W\nH. Monk.\nMiss Mary Danner, who has been\nvisiting Mrs. William Mudd in Bir\nmingham. Is expected home tomor\nrow.\nMrs. Carrie Clemmons of Cltronelle\nIs here on a visit to her parents.\nMiss Walee Miller of Brewton, Ala.,\narrived today to visit Miss Etta Mc\nGowan.\nHOLD TEACHERS' EXAMINATIONS.\nDOTHAN, ADA., Dec. 19.\u2014J. B. Dell,\nSuperintendent of Education in Hou*\u00bb''\nton County, ts conducting an examina\ntion In the court house here today, and\nmany applications for teachers' li\ncense to teach are being made.\nYOUNG Will BE REAPPOINTED.\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 19.\u2014Senator\nRoot and Representative Cocks, of the\nOyster Hay District in Congress, saw\nPresident Taft today relative to the\nre-appolntment of WRllam J. Youngs\nas United States District Attorney for\nthe Eastern District of New York.\nMr. Young is a close personal friend\nof Colonel Roosevelt. He has been in\noffice for two terms and It was said to\nday that he would be named again\nby President Taft.\n\u201cTo a Friend of Mme, From\nChristmas Sentiments.\na Friend of Thine.\u201d\u2014\nWe expect you to do a good bit of your Christmas shopping at this\nstore. The old bug-a-boo of what to buy for a man will immediately\nlose its dread once you step in our door. We've the best of everything\na man wears, and speaking from personal knowledge, we know a man\nis always best pleased with the kind of Christmas in gs we're ready to\nshow you. A myriad of fine choices:\nI\nBA I H ROBES.\nLOUNGING GOWNS.\nSMOKING JACKETS.\nNECKTIES.\nHANDKERCHIEFS,\nHOSIERY.\nGLOVES.\nSILK HATS.\nFUR GLOVES.\nSWhA 1 tK CUA13,\nWAISTCOATS,\nUMBRELLAS.\nWALKING STICKS.\nSTUD SETS.\nTRAVELING BAGS.\nCROSS LEATHER\nNOVELTIES. 5\u2018\nSOIL SURVEYS IN WMI\nHEI'DRT!) MADE TO V. S. AGR1CDL\nTl'RAL DEPAHTMEAT OK OVER\nFOUR THOUSAND ARl'ARE\nMILES OF TERRITORY,\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 19.\u2014The annual\nreport of the Chief of the Bureau of\nSoils, U. S. Department of Agricul\nture, shows that during the fiscal year\nsoil surveys were made of 4,224 square\nmiles of territory In the State of Ala\nbama, making a total of 22,592 tnfuare\nmiles, or 14,658,880 acres, that have\nbeen surveyed In the State since the\nBureau began work there. The work\nof Investigating the soli conditions has\nbeen In conjunction with the Agri\ncultural Department of the State.\nUp to date reports of the following\nsurveys have been printed. Autauga.\nBibb, Blount, Butler, Calhoun. Col\nbert, Cullman, Dallas, Etowah, Hale,\nHenry. Jefferson. Umar, Lauderdale,\nLee, Macon, Marlon, Montgomery, Sum\nter and Taladega counties; Fort Wayne\narea, comprising portions of DeKalb\nand Cherokee counties, and the Hunts\nville area, comprising portions of Lime\nstone and Madison counties. Surveys\nhave been finished and the reports are\nIn the hands of the printer for Bald\nwin, Chambers* Cofree and Tallapoosa\ncounties. Surveys are In progress In\nClarke and Pike counties. The new\nareas tthat are to be surveyed during\nthe winter are the counties of Mobile,\nwith 802 square miles; Jackson, with\n1,163 square miles; Randolph, with\n579 square miles, and Tuscaloosa with\n1,390 square miles.\nMessrs. Winston. Burke. Waldrop\nand Maynadler are the experts from\nthe Department who will conduct the\nsurveys, In conjunction with assistants\nfrom the State Agricultural Depart\nmnnt.\nA great demand ha* T>een made on\nthe Department at Washington for\ncopies of the reports \u00ab.f the various\nsurveys and for advance Information\nas to the character of the soils which\nare found by the experts. A largo\nnumber of these requests are from peo\nple outside of the State who wish\nto know If the soils are fertile and\nwhat they are best adapted to.\nTRAIN BRA7.II.I.I.N ARMY.\nBERI.IN, Dec. 19.\u2014Twenty German\narmy officers headed by a major, will\nbe selected from a number that have\nvolunteered to go to Dr axil and giro\nmilitary Instructions to the Brazilian\nArmy. The ofTlcers thus delegated\nwill resign their commissions they\nnow hold at home.\nBrazil requested the services of Ger\nman officers as a result of popular\ndiscontent with the, present training\nof its army and na.vy.\nMILUON8 OF\n\"Tummy\u201d Aches\nare on the way. They always come\nXmas for the big and little. Get\nready for them, mother. Thewhola\nhousehold wiU have to be helped.\nCASCARET8, win do it easily\nand naturally\u2014one at bed time to\neach member and keep the whole\nfamily well.\nBuy a 10c ho t CASCARETS\u2014wask's\ntreatment\u2014and have It baady to\n\u2022rery night. Itrnaa weak.\nTO DAIRYMEN AND COW OWNERS\nDRIED BEET PULP\nThe feed that makes milk like June pastures all the year round